The javadoc for `Files.list(Path)` states:

&gt; This method must be used within a try-with-resources statement or
&gt; similar control structure to ensure that the stream&#39;s open directory
&gt; is closed promptly after the stream&#39;s operations have completed.

The fix is simply to ensure that all use of `Files.list()` and `Files.find()` streams are closed after use, best done with try with resources handling:

    try(Stream&lt;Path&gt; stream = Files.list(target)) {
    	// do your str.forEach() calls with Files.deleteIfExists
        stream.forEach(Test::WrappedDeleteIfExists);
    }

Without the above fix - or switch to `File.listFiles()` - you can get weird behaviour in Windows Explorer: the deleted directory appears to exist but has no contents, and all operations report &quot;Access Denied&quot; errors. The problem remains until the current VM process ends.

